{
  "local_port": 33538,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some good sources for free instrumental music to use in video tutorials?",
  "response": "Creating engaging video tutorials often involves incorporating instrumental music to enhance the viewer's experience. Fortunately, there are numerous sources where you can find high-quality, free instrumental music suitable for your projects. Below are some of the best platforms offering free instrumental tracks, along with important considerations regarding their usage and licensing:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **YouTube Audio Library**\n\n- **Website:** [YouTube Audio Library](https://www.youtube.com/audiolibrary/music)\n- **Description:** A vast collection of free music and sound effects specifically curated for YouTube creators. The library includes a wide range of instrumental tracks across various genres.\n- **Licensing:** Most tracks are free to use in any of your YouTube videos with **no attribution required**, but some may require you to credit the artist. Always check the specific license attached to each track.\n\n### 2. **Free Music Archive (FMA)**\n\n- **Website:** [Free Music Archive](https://freemusicarchive.org/)\n- **Description:** An interactive library of high-quality, legal audio downloads directed by WFMU, the longest-running freeform radio station in the United States. It offers a diverse selection of instrumental music.\n- **Licensing:** Primarily uses **Creative Commons licenses**, allowing various types of usage. Be sure to verify the specific license for each track, especially regarding commercial use and attribution.\n\n### 3. **Incompetech**\n\n- **Website:** [Incompetech](https://incompetech.com/)\n- **Description:** Created by composer Kevin MacLeod, Incompetech hosts a large collection of royalty-free music, particularly instrumental pieces suitable for tutorials and presentations.\n- **Licensing:** Most tracks are available under the **Creative Commons Attribution License**, which requires you to credit the creator. An option to purchase a license to remove the attribution requirement is also available.\n\n### 4. **Bensound**\n\n- **Website:** [Bensound](https://www.bensound.com/)\n- **Description:** Offers a variety of free and premium royalty-free music tracks across multiple genres, including upbeat, corporate, and cinematic instrumental music.\n- **Licensing:** Free tracks require **attribution**. For projects where attribution isn't desired, you can purchase a license to use the music without crediting the artist.\n\n### 5. **Pixabay Music**\n\n- **Website:** [Pixabay Music](https://pixabay.com/music/)\n- **Description:** Part of the Pixabay platform, it provides a library of free music and sound effects that can be used in various projects, including video tutorials.\n- **Licensing:** All music on Pixabay is released under the **Pixabay License**, which allows use without attribution for both commercial and non-commercial purposes. However, you cannot redistribute or sell the music itself.\n\n### 6. **Jamendo**\n\n- **Website:** [Jamendo](https://www.jamendo.com/start)\n- **Description:** A community of independent artists offering a wide range of music. It\u2019s a great place to discover unique instrumental tracks.\n- **Licensing:** Offers both free and paid licenses. Free licenses are typically for personal use, while commercial use requires purchasing a suitable license. Always review the licensing terms for each track.\n\n### 7. **SoundCloud**\n\n- **Website:** [SoundCloud](https://soundcloud.com/)\n- **Description:** A popular platform where artists share their music, including many instrumental tracks available under Creative Commons licenses.\n- **Licensing:** Use the **Advanced Search** feature to filter tracks by their licensing type (e.g., Creative Commons). Ensure you understand and comply with the specific license terms, including attribution and usage restrictions.\n\n### 8. **ccMixter**\n\n- **Website:** [ccMixter](http://ccmixter.org/)\n- **Description:** A community music site featuring remixes and original tracks licensed under Creative Commons. It\u2019s particularly useful for finding instrumental music suitable for videos.\n- **Licensing:** Most music is available under **Creative Commons licenses**, which may require attribution or restrict commercial use. Verify each track's license before use.\n\n---\n\n### **Important Considerations When Using Free Music**\n\n1. **Check Licensing Terms:** Always read the specific license attached to each track. While many are free to use, some may require attribution or have restrictions on commercial use.\n\n2. **Attribution Requirements:** If a track requires you to credit the creator, ensure you include proper attribution in your video description or within the video itself as specified by the license.\n\n3. **Commercial Use:** If your tutorial is monetized or used for commercial purposes, confirm that the license permits such use. Some free licenses restrict usage to non-commercial projects.\n\n4. **Avoid Copyright Strikes:** Using music without proper licensing can lead to your videos being taken down or monetization being disabled. Always adhere to the licensing terms to protect your content.\n\n5. **Stay Updated:** Licensing terms can change, so periodically review the licenses of the tracks you\u2019ve used to ensure continued compliance.\n\n---\n\n### **Additional Tips**\n\n- **Use Royalty-Free Music Repositories:** Beyond the platforms listed above, consider exploring other royalty-free music libraries that offer free tiers.\n\n- **Create Custom Music:** If you have the resources, creating your own instrumental tracks ensures complete control over the licensing and suitability for your tutorials.\n\n- **Leverage Music Editing Software:** Tools like Audacity or GarageBand can help you customize tracks to better fit your video's pacing and tone.\n\n---\n\nBy utilizing these resources and adhering to their licensing requirements, you can enhance your video tutorials with professional-quality instrumental music without incurring additional costs. Always prioritize respecting the creators' rights by following the specified guidelines for each music track you use.",
